hat represent the progressive protest movements of the twentieth Century: labor, civil rights, the Vietnam War, LGBT rights, feminism and other minority rights. Make Art Not War can be enjoyed on aesthetic grounds alone, and also offers fascinating and revealing insights into twentieth century cultural, social and political history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aArtxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvSources. 0aPolitical posters, AmericanxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical posters, AmericanzNew York (State)zNew YorkvCatalogs. 0aProtest movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvSources. 0aSocial movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvSources. 7aART / American / General.2bisacsh1 aYoung, Ralph, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107289890 cprintz978147981367440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479888498423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479888498/original  a978-3-11-072898-9  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK